title: SpaceX Successfully Launches Military Spaceplane and Starlink Satellites in Doubleheader Event
text:
“`html
SpaceX aims for launch doubleheader to put military spaceplane and more Starlinks in orbit
SpaceX aims for launch doubleheader to put military spaceplane and more Starlinks in orbit
Kicking off a sky-lighting launch doubleheader, a powerful SpaceX Falcon Heavy rocket vaulted away from the Kennedy Space Center on Tuesday atop a torrent of flaming exhaust to put an unpiloted X-37B spaceplane into orbit for a classified, long-duration military mission.
Successful Launch of Falcon Heavy Rocket
The Falcon Heavy did its part, putting on a spectacular show for area residents and tourists as its 27 Merlin engines, nine in each of three strapped-together Falcon 9 boosters, ignited with a rush of flame and a ground-shaking roar at 8:07 p.m. EST.
The rocket then climbed away from the Kennedy Space Center atop more than 5 million pounds of thrust and lined up on a northeasterly trajectory, rapidly accelerating as the engines consumed propellants and the vehicle lost weight.
Challenges and Delays
The launching originally was scheduled for Dec. 10, but the flight was delayed by predicted bad weather and then by trouble with ground equipment. The rocket was hauled off the launch pad and back to a SpaceX hangar for subsequent work. It was rolled back out to pad 39A on Wednesday.
